text:
East 113th Street, west from Third Ave.  Note the elevated road bed of the New York Central Railroad on Park Ave.

November 27, 1936.

W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Art project.

2065 to 2069 Third Ave., (left, elevated line thereon), at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of East 113th Street (right), showing prominently 3 tenements forming a 76 X 104 foot plot that will be cleared according to the New York Times of September 22, 1937. This property, a part of the old Bogart farm was purchased by Captain Johannes Benson about 1696 and held into his family until today, being transferred by the estate of Annie W. Gould, a direct descendant. See the aforementioned newspaper for a fuller account.

November 14, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

172 to 156 (left to right) East 113th Street, south side, between Third and Lexington Aves., as viewed in a westward direction. Shown in the center are three small frame buildings, numbered 168 to 164.

November 14, 1937.
P.L. Sperr

164-168 East 113th Street, south side of Third Avenue.
These are all three-story frame houses.

1932.
J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.

Negative No. 148.
